    <h1>Business Entities</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Company">Company</h3>
<p>A company describes an organisation that consists of employees and asset=
s.&nbsp;</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>A company can have multiple employees</li>
<li>A company can have multiple roles</li>
<li>A company can have access to multiple assets</li>
<li>A company can have access to multiple assettypeproperties with the leve=
l of access defined individually per assettypeproperty</li>
<li>A company can not be linked to another company in any way</li>
<li>A company can not be deleted</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-CompanyAsset">CompanyAsset</h3>
<p>A companyAsset contains the list of assets that are available to a certa=
in company.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.1">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>Each companyasset has to define the type of link from the company to th=
e asset (e.g. owner, manufacturer, ...)</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Asset">Asset</h3>
<p>An asset describes an object that sends data to RAS. It should be seen a=
s an implementation of a certain assettype.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.2">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>An asset can be linked to multiple companies</li>
<li>An asset can be linked to only one assettype</li>
<li>An asset must have an assettype</li>
<li>An asset must have an assetproperty record for each assettypeproperty t=
hat is linked to the asset's assettype</li>
<li>An asset is an audited entity</li>
<li>An asset can not be deleted</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-AssetType">AssetType</h3>
<p>An assettype describes the definition of an asset. Each assettype can in=
herit from another assettype. In logical terms, it should be seen as the in=
terface of the asset.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.3">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>An assettype can be used by multiple assets</li>
<li>An assettype can have multiple assettypeproperties</li>
<li>An assettype is an audited entity</li>
<li>An assettype can link to itself which then defines the baseassettype</l=
i>
<li>An asset is an audited entity</li>
<li>An assettype can not be deleted when it is in use by at least one other=
 assettype</li>
<li>An assettype can not be deleted when it is in use by at least one asset=
</li>
<li>An assettype can not have a baseassettypeid that is equal to it's own i=
d</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-AssetTypeProperty">AssetTypeProperty</h3>
<p>An assettypeproperty always belongs to a single assettype. It describes =
a property by name, type and origin.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.4">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>An assettypeproperty must be linked to only one assettype</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty can be linked to multiple assetproperties</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty must have a name</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty must define the origin of each property using asse=
tpropertyorigin</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty must define the type of the property using assetty=
pepropertytype</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty can be managed by multiple companies where each is=
 defined by companyassettypeproperty</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty can reference to a post-processor calculation usin=
g popcalculationreference</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty is an audited entity</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty can not be deleted when it is in use by at least o=
ne assetproperty</li>
<li>An assettypeproperty can not be altered when it is in use by at least o=
ne assetproperty</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-AssetTypePropertyType">AssetTypePropertyType</h3=
>
<p>The AssetTypePropertyType defines the type of the value that an AssetPro=
pertyValue can have for an AssetTypeProperty.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.5">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>The available types can not be altered by an application</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-AssetPropertyOrigin">AssetPropertyOrigin</h3>
<p>The origin of a property explains where the property originated from. At=
 the moment of writing it can be 'sensor', 'static' or 'postprocessor'.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.6">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>The available origins can not be altered&nbsp;by an application</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-AssetProperty">AssetProperty</h3>
<p>An asset implements a certain assettype, hence also implements the prope=
rties that the assettype (and its base assettypes) defines. The implementat=
ions of these assettypeproperties are stored in the database as assetproper=
ties.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.7">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>An assetproperty must link to one asset</li>
<li>An assetproperty must link to one assettypeproperty</li>
<li>An assetproperty is an audited entity</li>
<li>An assetproperty can have multiple assetpropertyvalues (one property ca=
n have multiple values)</li>
<li>An assetproperty can not be deleted or altered when it is in use by at =
least one assetpropertyvalue</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-CompanyAssetTypeProperty">CompanyAssetTypeProper=
ty</h3>
<p>A companyassettypeproperty defines which company has access to which ass=
ettypeproperty and whether the company can edit and/or delete the assettype=
property.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.8">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>Each companyassettypeproperty must refer to a single company</li>
<li>Each companyassettypeproperty must refer to a single assettypeproperty<=
/li>
<li>A companyassettypeproperty must specify if the company can write and/or=
 delete the assettypeproperty</li>
<li>A companyassettypeproperty can have only one record per company and ass=
ettypeproperty</li>
<li>A companyassettypeproperty can be deleted at any time</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-User">User</h3>
<p>A user describes a single logon entity which can be granted access to an=
 application. The structure is based on the Microsoft Asp.Net Identity Fram=
ework.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.9">Business rules:&nbsp;</h5>
<ul>
<li>A user must have a unique email address</li>
<li>A user must have a password</li>
<li>A user's password can not be retreivable from the database, its equalit=
y can only be verified by a hashing algorithm</li>
<li>A user must be able to reset it's password through token generation</li=
>
<li>A user can not be deleted</li>
<li>A user can be locked out</li>
<li>A user can only have one company</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-CompanyUserRole">CompanyUserRole</h3>
<p>A companyuserrole defines which roles have been granted to a companyuser=
</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.10">Business rules:</h5>
<ul>
<li>A companyuserrole must refer to a single companyuser</li>
<li>A&nbsp;companyuserrole must refer to a single role</li>
<li>A companyuserrole can be deleted at any time</li>
<li>A companyuserrole is an audited entity</li>
<li>A companyuserrole can not contain a role that is not available to the c=
ompany to wich the companyuser belongs</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Permission">Permission</h3>
<p>A permission identifies a certain action that can be secured</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.11">Business rules:</h5>
<ul>
<li>A permission should clearly describe the action that is being secured</=
li>
<li>A permission can be used by multiple roles</li>
<li>A permission can not be directly assigned to a user or company (all sec=
urity is defined by roles)</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Role">Role</h3>
<p>A role consists of a number of permissions and is usually named in a fun=
ctional manner such as Support Engineer.</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.12">Business rules:</h5>
<ul>
<li>A role must have at least one permission</li>
<li>A role must have a clear name</li>
<li>A role can not be deleted while it is in use by at least one user or co=
mpany</li>
<li>Only users or companies can have roles assigned to them</li>
<li>A role is an audited entity</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Dashboard">Dashboard</h3>
<p>A dashboard describes a list of widgets and datasources which can be des=
igned by the user</p>
<h5 id=3D"BusinessEntities-Businessrules:.13">Business rules:</h5>
<ul>
<li>Each dashboard must be linked to a single user</li>
<li>The structure of the dashboard must be saved in xml format</li>
<li>A dashboard is an audited entity</li>
<li>Dashboards can be shared, this would however create a copy of the origi=
nal dashboard</li>
</ul>
